{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627562"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:49:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:49:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17127"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17127"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.02,0.04,0.12,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9817"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68700"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9817"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17127"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54157"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5008"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22995"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23017"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68700"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman is prescribed dabigatran for stroke prevention in atrial fibrillation. She asks how this medication prevents blood clots from forming.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of dabigatran?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Binds directly to thrombin\u0027s active site","Blocks tissue factor synthesis","Activates protein C pathway","Enhances antithrombin III activity","Inhibits vitamin K epoxide reductase"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDabigatran is a direct thrombin inhibitor, which works by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding directly to thrombin\u0027s active site\u003C/strong\u003E, preventing it from converting fibrinogen to fibrin. This direct binding allows them to inhibit both free and clot-bound thrombin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks tissue factor synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism of any current anticoagulants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivates protein C pathway\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as direct thrombin inhibitors do not primarily affect the protein C system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances antithrombin III activity\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of heparin, which requires antithrombin III as a cofactor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits vitamin K epoxide reductase\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of warfarin, which prevents vitamin K-dependent clotting factor synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnlike heparin which requires antithrombin III as a cofactor, direct thrombin inhibitors can function independently by directly binding to thrombin. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Direct thrombin inhibitors work by binding directly to thrombin\u0027s active site, preventing fibrinogen conversion to fibrin.","Direct thrombin inhibitors can inhibit both free and clot-bound thrombin.","Unlike heparin, direct thrombin inhibitors do not require antithrombin III as a cofactor."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54157"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17127"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54157"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T11:27:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T11:27:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9817"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68700"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici